**Q7: How do you test secured endpoints?**

**A:** With `spring-security-test`:
```java
@WebMvcTest(OrderController.class)
class OrderControllerTest {
  @Autowired MockMvc mvc;

  @Test @WithMockUser(username = "alice", roles = "USER")
  void user_can_list() throws Exception {
    mvc.perform(get("/api/orders")).andExpect(status().isOk());
  }

  @Test
  void anonymous_gets_401() throws Exception {
    mvc.perform(get("/api/orders")).andExpect(status().isUnauthorized());
  }

  @Test @WithMockUser(roles = "USER")
  void user_cannot_delete() throws Exception {
    mvc.perform(delete("/api/orders/42")).andExpect(status().isForbidden());
  }

  @Test @WithMockJwt(claims = @Claim(name = "scope", value = "orders:write"))
  void write_scope_can_create() throws Exception {
    mvc.perform(post("/api/orders").content("{...}")).andExpect(status().isCreated());
  }
}
```
**Rule:** for every rule you write, add a positive AND negative test. Silent misconfiguration is Spring Security's biggest failure mode — tests catch it.
